{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11824"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.12,0.02,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84696"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84696"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review. However, a rapid antigen test for COVID-19 conducted before entering the clinic returns a positive result. He is advised to go home and await a telehealth appointment. On review, he reports a three-day history of fatigue, fevers and dry cough, worse at night that is affecting his sleep. The fatigue has been constant and has kept him mostly in bed. He denies chest tightness, chest pain or shortness of breath at rest. He has mild anxiety that is managed by a psychologist. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has had three doses of the COVID-19 vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for the current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular paracetamol and rest","Nirmatrelvir plus ritonavir","Oral amoxicillin","Oral prednisolone","Inhaled budesonide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular paracetamol and rest\u003C/strong\u003E are important elements of supportive care for mild COVID-19 infection. Most cases will resolve within 10 days, especially in this young patient with no significant comorbidities and who is vaccinated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENirmatrelvir plus ritonavir\u003C/strong\u003E, antivirals, are highly effective at reducing hospitalisation if started within five days of symptom onset. They are indicated for patients who are deemed high risk of developing severe disease. The patient in this stem has no risk factors for severe disease and therefore would not be considered eligible for antiviral therapy.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled budesonide\u003C/strong\u003E is an inhaled corticosteroid often used as a preventer in asthma management. While some studies have suggested it may reduce the risk of urgent care visits or hospitalisations in COVID-19 patients, its use is not routinely recommended for mild cases like this one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral corticosteroid. It is not recommended for mild COVID-19 cases managed in the community. Systemic corticosteroids are typically reserved for hospitalised patients requiring oxygen therapy or with severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is a penicillin antibiotic and therefore is not indicated to treat COVID-19, a viral infection. Secondary bacterial pneumonia is a risk following COVID-19, so this must be monitored for.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Many patients with mild COVID-19 infection, fully vaccinated and without risk of severe disease, can be managed in the community with supportive care."],"references":["Rodriguez-Guerra M, Jadhav P, Vittorio TJ. Current treatment in COVID-19 disease: a rapid review. Drugs in context. 2021;10. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7850293/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68984"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T12:04:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T12:04:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4429"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84696"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r